Part I - Ford GoBike System Data¶

By Darine BATTIKH¶

Introduction¶

Ford GoBike is a bike sharing system located and covering the San FranciscoBay area. It provides more than 4,000 bikes distributed across different accessible locations allowing customers to get bikes from one station and return to any other station in the system, making them ideal, accessible, and convenient for one-way trips, for special and urgent occasions. The bikes are available for use 24 hours/day, all days of the week, and all days of the year. Customers have the possibility to become subscribers through a monthly or yearly subscriptions or simply purchase one ride for a determined number of hours.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Ford GoBike System Data is a dataframe was compoed of 16 columns and 183412 rows, before the cleaning process. It was necssary to clean the data before moving the explanatory analysis and now it is composed of 12 columns and 183215. The dataframe has different data types like objects, integers (64), and float64.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

This dataset is really rich to analyse and interpret. The main features that would be interesting to explore are:

  1. Most timing when the trips were taken considering the time of day, day of the week, and month of the year.
  2. Duration of a trip (bike ride)
  3. Characteristics of the members in terms of age, gender, and user type. With that being said, the company can work on the core segment to convert more customers into subscribers and to attract new members.
  4. The relationship between the user type and the timing and duration of bike rides (whether the user type affect these variables)
  5. Most used bikes for the trips. We can conclude whether there is a special type of bike for rides or prefered by members.
  6. Start and End Stations. This can provide helpful insights to make improvement in the less considered stations and implement marketing strategies to attract more members and gain more subscribers.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

To find interesting insights and answer these questions, all the variables will be required. The following variables will be the main ones: the trip duration, the start and end station, the bike id, the users' types, the members' ages and genders, the date (time, day, month, and year). All the features will be used in the open investigation through studying each variable separately or in relationships with other variables.

def create_plot(data, x, order, title, xlabel, ylabel, isSubplot, sp1=1, sp2=2, sp3=1, y=None, withRotation=False, plotType='countPlot', height=None,) :
    #Histogramme on the left about the name of the start location
    if isSubplot :
        plt.subplot(sp1,sp2,sp3)
    sb.countplot(data=data, x=x, color=color[0], order=order, y=y)
    if withRotation :
        plt.xticks(rotation = 90); 
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    
def create_pie_plot(data, order, title, labels, colors) :
    plt.pie(order, labels =labels, colors = colors , startangle = 90, counterclock = False, autopct='%.0f%%', radius = 10);
    plt.title(title, size = 15)
    plt.axis('square');  

def create_bar_plot(x, height, colors, xlabel, ylabel, title) :
    plt.bar(x=x, height=height, color=colors);
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show();
    
def create_histogramme (data, x, bins, color, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    plt.hist(data = data, x = x, bins = bins, color = color)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show();

Observation¶

For the start location, customers and/subscribers start mostly from the following location respectively: Market St at 10th St, San Fransisco Caltrain Station 2, and Berry St at 4th St.

For the end location, they stop mostly at the following respective locations: San Fransisco Caltrain Station 2, Market St at 10th St, and Montgomery St BART Station.

We can say the these are the most famous stations for bike rent. The choice of these stations can be dependent on many variables: preferences of the customers, famousness of these location compared to other ones, more targeted marketing and promotion acitivities are focused on these areas, or simply closeness to the customers.

To be able to answer these questions, it is required to have more data that is not present in this dataset.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The duration in seconds was not clearly indicative to the trip duration, for that, it was crucial to transform the data from seconds to minutes to be intrepeted.

The start and end stations were really numerous. No transformation has been made, but only the top 10 were considered for interpretation. Still, it was really valuable as information for this analysis because there was no difference to provide insightful conclusions.

The dataframe has only one month, February, which did not allow the analysis of the rides distrubtion per month.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The data was clear before starting the univariate exploration, for that, only the creation of new columns was required. The columns that wew generated are: Duration in minutes, day columns, day names column, age columns to help further investigation and interpretations.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The relationships between features in the three visualizations strengthened each other and provided interesting interpretations.

Female has longer rides than males.

Older age groups have longer rides than younger groups.

Customers have more ride bikes on weekends than subscribers while subscriber have a consistent rides all over the week.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The most surprising observation was that the first longest trip for females and kinda for males is for people aged between 50 and 60. Also, for the other gender, the longest ride belongs to those between 40 and 50. In contrast, younger generations have shorter rides.

Another interesting interpretation is that the females has the longest rides, in almost all age groups, than males.

Conclusions¶

There is no significant difference in the start and end locations. They seemed all accessible by all members. There was no difference in the usage of specific bikes reflecting that members are indifferent regarding the available bikes (no preference).

Subscribers are almost 8 times more than customers, yet, customers tend to have longer bike rides especially on the weekends. Subscirebers have a consistent usage of bikes all over the week. For the weekdays, there was a slight differnce in days with Thursday and Tuesday having the most rides.The longest rides are on weekends, and all trips don't exceed 200 minutes per day. Generally, all rides start and ends on the same day

Males are more than half female and other gender (75%), yet, female have more and longer trips.

People with most trip are aged between 30 and 35 years old, which can be explained by the fact that this age group is the most present in the dataframe.

On average, most trips last 10 minutes and more than a half of trips are less than 30 minutes.

When it comes to gender and age groups, people above 40, in almost all gender types, have longer trip duration than younger people, considering that we considered people above 20 years old in this analysis.
